    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:30a4a148-c873-442f-a635-d47dd6f5bea8",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a bright-eyed 2-year-old girl with curly chestnut hair and rosy, cherubic cheeks — though today those cheeks are flushed with fever. She is brought to the pediatric emergency department by her mother, who is visibly anxious. {patientName} sits on her mother's lap clutching a worn stuffed bunny, and between intermittent bouts of crying she can be heard taking rapid, shallow breaths with a subtle but audible grunt on exhalation. She occasionally coughs — a wet, productive-sounding cough that makes her wince — and has been refusing her favorite snacks since yesterday.\n\nAt home, {patientName} lives with her parents and a 5-year-old brother in a suburban apartment. She attends a daycare center three days per week, where a respiratory illness has been circulating among the children. She enjoys finger painting, singing nursery rhymes, and chasing the family cat around the living room. Her mother reports that {patientName} has been sleeping fitfully, waking up crying and tugging at her chest, and that her breathing has looked \"different\" — noticeably faster than normal.\n\nOn physical examination, {patientName} appears mildly to moderately unwell. She is tachypneic with a respiratory rate of 46 breaths per minute and has an oxygen saturation of 93% on room air. Her temperature is 38.9°C. Auscultation of the lungs reveals decreased air entry and fine crackles at the right lower lobe, with dullness to percussion in the same area. There is mild subcostal retracting noted. Her heart rate is 138 bpm, and she is maintaining adequate perfusion.\n\n{patientName}'s mother is a kindergarten teacher and her father works as a delivery driver. The family does not smoke in the home, though the building is older and her mother suspects some mold near a window in the children's bedroom. {patientName} is up to date on her routine immunizations except for the most recent flu vaccine, which was missed this season due to a scheduling conflict. She has not required any prior hospitalizations."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:23e17b66-3ba0-487b-bcdb-348ec543919c",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} was born at 39 weeks gestation via uncomplicated vaginal delivery with no neonatal complications. Her growth and development have been appropriate for her age — she is meeting all major milestones. She has a history of one prior episode of viral bronchiolitis at 10 months of age managed at home with supportive care. No prior hospitalizations or surgical procedures. She has no known chronic illnesses such as asthma or recurrent ear infections, though her mother notes she tends to get \"chest colds\" more than her brother does. {patientName} has no significant dietary restrictions and is fully weaned. Her immunization record is complete except for the current season's influenza vaccine. There is no history of foreign body aspiration or known immunodeficiency. She has been attending daycare, where a respiratory illness has been circulating for the past two weeks."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
